    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="preparation">Donal Phillipson, in answer to Steve Fuller, who, in turn was responding
to Richardson and Shanks (whew!), claims:</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="22" relname="span">

&amp;gt;First, there
appears to be ample evidence that scientists do not need philosophers&apos;
help to do good science;  and usually derive any related philosophy
directly from the science rather than through the discipline of philosophy.&amp;lt;</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="23" relname="span">

Of course.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="14" relname="span"> And, on the other hand, there is ample evidence that scientists
have frequently used philosopher&apos;s help in doing good science;</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="elaboration"> and
have derived some related science directly from the philosophy rather than
through the discipline of their science.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="19" relname="span">
[I&apos;m thinking of the case of the origins of modern cosmology, 1932-1940,
with special focus upon the work of E.A. Milne.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="8" relname="condition"> If you&apos;re interested in
the evidence I present,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="15" relname="span"> check out &quot;Philosophical Midwifery and the Birth
Pangs of Modern Cosmology&quot;, _AMERICAN JL. OF PHYSICS_, Jan. 93]</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="21" relname="span">

My main point in turning Philipson&apos;s assertion on its head, however, is to
point out the futility of general claims on these issues.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="11" relname="condition"> If we want to talk
usefully about the relations between philosophy, science and the various
social perspectives on either or both,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="16" relname="span"> then we have come to the end of the
purely generalities.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="17" relname="span"> Gentlefolks, it&apos;s time to get down to cases;</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="12" relname="elaboration"> empirical
claims only, from this point on?</segment>
